SUMMARY:Econometrics – Jack Jewson (Monash) – Bayesian computation for 
 high-dimensional Gaussian Graphical Models with spike-and-slab priors
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Jack Jewson: “Bayesian computation for high-dimensional Gauss
 ian Graphical Models with spike-and-slab priors”\nhttps://sites.google.c
 om/view/jack-jewson-academic-profile/home\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us
 /j/82137514093?pwd=KSb1ZXIyCKxNbsIkrno9M8a3jpA8CY.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle M
 aps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nGaussian grap
 hical models are widely used to infer dependence structures in data. Bayes
 ian methods are appealing to quantify uncertainty associated with structur
 al learning and to incorporate available prior and external information in
 to analyses. However\, computational demands have limited their applicatio
 n when the number of variables is large. We propose fully Bayesian algorit
 hms that probably scale well to high dimensions when the data-generating p
 recision matrix is sparse. We further show how the spike-and-slab prior fr
 amework allows for the incorporation of external network data to help impr
 ove inference and interpretability when the number of observations is smal
 l relative to the number of variables. We use our methodology to investiga
 te dependence structures in COVID-19 cases across the US and to explore wh
 ether connectedness on facebook can explain partial correlations between g
 eographically distant counties.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82137514093?pwd=KSb1ZXIyCKxNbsIkrno9M8a3jpA8C
 Y.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
