SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Nicholas Chiang (University of Melbourne)
  – Childhood Exposure to Social Assistance and Adult Outcomes: Evidence 
 from SMTA
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Nicholas Chiang: “Childhood Exposure to Social Assistance and
  Adult Outcomes: Evidence from SMTA”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.go
 o.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nI study the long-term effects of chil
 dhood exposure to social assistance in a setting with endogenous applicati
 on\, discretionary approval\, and repeated programme participation. Focusi
 ng on Singapore’s Short-to-Medium-Term Assistance (SMTA) programme\, I d
 evelop a two-stage framework to recover the effect of childhood exposure a
 fter accounting for selection. In the first stage\, I estimate a structura
 l model of parental labour supply and welfare application decisions to rec
 over persistent parental heterogeneity\, including earning capacity and pr
 eferences for programme participation. In the second stage\, I relate chil
 dren’s adult income outcomes to their childhood SMTA exposure histories 
 while accounting for parental heterogeneity and approval-stage selection. 
 I find that greater childhood exposure to SMTA is associated with higher i
 ncome in adulthood. Policy simulations suggest that expanding eligibility 
 generates larger gains in adult income per dollar spent than increasing be
 nefit levels.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:213bb739350ec2c775d449ff5fbb16f7@generated
DTSTAMP:20260427T195929Z
