SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Longcan Li (University of Melbourne) – 
 A Flexible Multiplicative Unobserved Component Model for Reduced-Rank Matr
 ix Time Series
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Longcan Li: “A Flexible Multiplicative Unobserved Component M
 odel for Reduced-Rank Matrix Time Series”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.a
 pp.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nHigh-dimensional matrix-variate 
 time series arise naturally in economics and finance\, yet existing models
  are confined to bilinear (Kronecker) structures that preclude linear cros
 s-sectional dependencies. This paper introduces a nonlinear dynamic factor
  model for matrix-valued time series built on a reduced-rank decomposition
  that the rank-r common component captures all systematic co-movement acro
 ss the nxk matrix. Just as cointegration restricts the long-run impact mat
 rix to have reduced rank r\, our framework imposes a low-rank signal struc
 ture that parsimoniously encodes common dynamics shared across variables a
 nd units. Unlike the static cointegration vectors\, however\, the factor m
 atrices are time-varying\, with their joint evolution governed by a linear
  VAR in the latent state. Although the latent dynamics are linear\, the ob
 servation map is nonlinear\, enabling the model to capture complex\, non-G
 aussian dependencies while remaining analytically tractable. We establish 
 identification via a top-block normalization. Estimation proceeds via a Gi
 bbs sampler with a conjugate matrix-normal prior. Monte Carlo experiments 
 confirm accurate factor recovery across a range of sample sizes and factor
  dimensions. In a DSGE-based experiment with a three-region macroeconomic 
 model\, our model consistently outperforms the Matrix Autoregression model
  on moments estimation accuracy.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:2a670d9e205e3d949cf075616ae93639@generated
DTSTAMP:20260427T195929Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260427T195929Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260508T145000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260508T153000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Adam Wang (University of Melbourne) – B
 ayesian Semiparametric Multitask Learning with Sequential Monte Carlo
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Adam Wang: “Bayesian Semiparametric Multitask Learning with S
 equential Monte Carlo”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKur
 X9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nWe propose a novel Bayesian semiparametric multitas
 k learning method. To avoid misspecification of the data generating proces
 s\, we use Bayesian empirical likelihoods to infer both local and shared p
 arameters. It is well-known that the Bayesian empirical likelihood posteri
 or is challenging to sample from\, due to its typically non-convex support
 . This computational challenge is amplified in multitask settings where th
 e likelihood arises from a combination of multiple datasets\, further comp
 licating the posterior support structure. To address this\, we develop a S
 equential Monte Carlo algorithm that involves draws from a sequence of Bay
 esian adjusted empirical likelihood posteriors with decreasing adjustment 
 levels. This adjustment level sequence mitigates irregularities in interme
 diate steps\, allowing particles to explore the posterior space efficientl
 y. We show that the intermediate adjusted posterior is continuous in the a
 djustment parameter and converges to the target original posterior as the 
 adjustment level approaches zero\, thus guaranteeing algorithmic convergen
 ce. The efficiency and convergence of our method are demonstrated through 
 a simulation study.
END:VEVENT
